{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_galshar_ver01/data/sn98068396/00393348112/1957101801/0433.xml":{"full_text":"Aboard The Forrestal\nNight Recovery Of Planes By NATO Carrier\nPacks Much Drama On Norwegian Sea\nBy K'nv RT> n s'MS\n(Special Writer)\nAb~vd th-> FoTestal\u2014Oct. 8\u2014A\nf\u2014\" n^hts apri the writer stood on\nthe \u201cPry Fly\" bridge through the\n\u2022rreh* to watch the recovery of th'ee\ndifferent types rf aircraft returning\nt\u201c 'he Fo\u2019-'-estal af'er night nvssions.\nThe Norwegian Sea was choppy but\ngenerally calm and tho weather\nmost of the time\u2014was satisfactory.\nHowever, there were times when\nthe h'p carrier elided into dark\na'ea.s in which sleet, rain or snow\nfell heavily from above. On several\noccasions. a\u2019\u2019C\"aft were landed in\na d'amabc accomplishment on each\nthese limited conditions and it was\naccomplished on each occasion\nDuring these Operation Strikeback\nexercises, pilots are flying over\nNorthern waters up to about 70 Lati\ntude. and an accident at night might\nwell cost them their lives.\nThe ship is constantly in touch\nwith returning aircraft and when\nthey are about 70 miles out. one be\ngins to prepare for their approach.\nThey report in as they come closer,\nand the captain begins to head the\nbig carrier into the wind and get up\nsufficient speed to give pilots at\nleast 30 knots for landing. The\n\u201cdeck apes\" begin to get ready to\nreceive the\u2019plane on the flight deck.\nIn the \u201cP'v Fly\" control tower,\nthe arresting gear 'huge cables\nwhich stop the lanindg aircraft' is\nset for the particular load it is to be\nexpected to take. On one landing\nthe other night, involving an A3D\njet bomber, the bomber was unable\nto ditch most o' its fuel and landed\nheavy.\nThe arresting gear was set to stop\nn 52.000-pound aircraft. The jot.\nbomber came in a little fast and\nused all except two feet of the ar\nresting gear. It was estimated she\nweighed 49.000 pounds when she hit\nthe deck doing approximately 150\nknots.\nOn another occasion, an aircraft\nwas approaching for a landing when\nthe carrier glided into a heavy snow\nstorm With vision bad. the jet\nneeded four passes at the carrier\nbefore it could get safely down and\nan alternate landhig in Norway was\nbeing emside-cd when he made it.\nSince his 'upI was approaching the\nPoint whe-e he would have to fly to\nNorway without more delay if he\nwas to go ther/*' and since there\nwas a suspicion that, th\" hook on his\nfuselage had been damaged, it was\nessential that this aircraft come\naboard without further extenive de\nlay.\nA jet bomber with a broken wind\nshield. another with fur! gauges in\noperative and one with its heating\nsystr.m out. were all landed in the\nsnare of a few hours by jhe Forres\nts! recently. These recoveries were\nall made in northern waters, without\nthe benefit of any moon. In other\nwords, finding a downed pilot in\ns\u201dch conditions, even though boats\naboard the carrier a\u2019e constantly\nRev A Collins, past o r of\nl ibe-tv Baptist church, of Appo\nmattox is conducting a revival at\nSprint.: Creek Baptist church this\nweek. The public is cordially in\nvited.\nMr. and M\u2019s W A Shorter, of\nRoanoke, arc visiting their son and\ndaughter-in-law. Mr and Mrs. How\nard Shorter, ibis week.\nM s Beta Ma-lin. of Ashland, who\nhas been visiting her daughter in\nBlnefield, W Va visited her sister,\nM\u2019s Thornton Cunningham, last\nweek.\nSonny Bailey, who is attending\nI. ngwood College this fail, is work\nina part-tune in the men\u2019s depart\nment of P\u2019,Mw:n's Department Store\nin Farmville.\nMrs. Sudic Watson, M s W D\nHunter. M s. Margaret Watson and\nM'ss Terrell Ham-v sr-mt Saturday\nand Sunday in Williamsburg and\nJamestow n\nThose attending the funeral of\nM s Sallir Slavic in Lynchburg\nwere M\u2019ss Fannie B Shot ter. Ned\nShorter. Mr. and M s W A. Shorter.\nMr. and M s Howard Shorter and\nM's. Dick Short\nMr. and M s W A Shorter were\nluncheon guest of Miss Fannie\nBelle Shorter Tuesday\nMixed Right\nand Delivered\nRight to You\nfor driveways or other con\nstruction, we supply concrete\nmixed to your order. Prompt\ndelivery.\n\"Ice, Coal, Fuel Oil\nand Cement\"\nW. C. Newman\nCompany\nFarmville, Va.\nPhone 41\nmanned when recoveries a\u2019-e being\nmade and though destroyers follow\nclosely behind, would have been\ndoubtful. And a pilot can only last\na matter of minutes in these wate\u201ds.\nPerhaps somewhat longer if he is\nwearing a rubberized suit, though\nnet lone in any event.\nThe eight carriers involved hi this\nexc cise ha'e certainly demon\nstrated their ability to launch aerial\nstrikes continuously in northern\nwaters in daylight and darkness\nand accidents were held to an abso\nlute minimum.\nOne neaT'-collision occured aboard\nthe Porrestal. witnessed by this\nwriter on the Admiral's bridge. The\nPorrestal was turning ha\u00bb-d star\nboard to take up position near the\nCarrier Essex. The cruiser Albany\nwas proceeding to the same station\nand the Porrestal cut in front of the\npath of the Albany.\nThe ships proceeded on this col\nlision course for some time. Neither\nship checked its progress and the\nbow of the Albanv moved steadily j\ncloser from the left At this stage,*\ntnqui'-ies began to be made and\nquestions raised aboard the Forres-\n'al\u2014and no doubt aboard the Al\nbany. At about the same time, sev\neral officers aboard both ships\nrealized that if the two ships fol\nlowed their courses for another\nminute, they would collide.\nThe fi\u2019st sure indication of the\nseriousness of the situation, as far\nas the writer was concerned, came\nwhen he heard the report that the\nAlbany was doing a full astern\nNevertheless, the ships glided on\ntoward one another, the momentum\nof the Albany carrying her forward.\nThe Albany was in a position to\nstrike the Fnrrestal on its port side.\nBy this time, the Forrestal was also\nfull astern.\nWith hundreds of eyes on her, the\nAlbany, slowing steadily, approach\ned closer and closer, until she\nreached a position about 150 or 200\nyards away. Her stern began to'\nswing around and. as it did. the\ntwo ships passed parallel, approxi\nmately 100 yards apart.!\nIt was a near collision, which\nwould have been a trag'c moment\nfor both ships, and probShly their i\nskippers. Two sizable ships were in\nvolved and the impact from such a\ncollision would have been enough to\nknock aircraft, overboard and done\nserious damage to both ships,\nthough the Forrestal fully loaded\ndisplaces about 75.000 tons to the\nc'-uisers less than cne-third that\namount.\nTlrs dramatic event took place on\na day of replenishing, when a vast\nairay of warships and supply ships\nwere concentrated in a small area.\nAt various times during the day one\n.could count six or seven carriers\nvisible from. the bridge of the Fbr\nrestal, battleships, cruisers, des\ntroyers and supply ships in all di\nrections.\nOne cf the most impressive things\nabout a huge fleet, such as this, is\nthe constant activity which must al\nways be m progress while ships a> e\nunderway. The deck crew never\nseems to rest aboard the Forrestal\nduring an of'ensivc operation of this\nkind. Maintenance wo k on the han\ngar dock never ceases, and the job\nof maintaining course, and position\nis constant.\nIn a sense, it is like being in Las\nV<sas, Nevada. No matter when\nyou v.-ake up at night 'and despite\nthe termendous roar of jet launch\nings and aircraft landings, and other\nis 4 o'clock in the morning, or 12\no'clock at night, something of inter\nest is always going on.\nIt is unlike Las Vegas in that no\nliquor or gambling is permitted\naboat'd ship, despite the fact that\nthe U. S. Navy is the only one in\nthe world which does not permit\neven the officers to have alcoholic\nbeverages of any kind.\nSondy River Items\nAfter 80 Years of Life, Mrs. W. B. Gates\nAnticipates Visits; Feels Fit, Fine\nJack Frost paid his first visit of\nthe season to this section of the\ncountry Saturday night. As he\nwielded his frosty brush, he wrought\nmany changes. Where there were\nbeautiful green fields and plants,\nnow man and vegetation bow in\nsubmission.\nRev. and Mrs. T. O. Herndon and\ndaughters. Virginia Overton and\nElizabeth Rose, were dinner guests\nof M\". and Mrs. James Gates, and\n'amily. Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Fred Powers and\nson. Danny, of Dickmson county,\n\u25a0spent Friday night with Mr. and\nM\u2019s. W A. Odham. They were en\n>\u2019oute to Alexandria, and also\nstopped in Richmond to visit Mr.\nPowe -s' father at the Medical Col\nlege Hospital.\nMr. and Mrs. William Shearer and\nchildren, Michael and Lora, from\nSouth America, friends of Mr. and\nMrs F. L. Louis, spent Monday\nn\u2019ght with them on their way to\nPennsylvania, where they will make\ntheir home.\nM\u2019s. Lynn Weekends in Farim ille\nM:'.s. Irene Lynn spent a very\npleasant week end with a friend in\nFarmville.\nMr. and M\u2019s. Jesse Gates called\n\"n Mr. and Mis Drewry Gates Sun\nday.\nM\u2019s R F Simmons, of Norfolk,\nspent the week end with Mr. and\nMrs. Mercer Gilliam. Mrs. Sim\nmons. a former resident of this\ncommunity, enjoys returning, es\npecially in the spring and fall when\n\u201che can observe the many changes\nin nature, as well as the neighbor\nhoed.\nJ T Bruce dined with the Bassos\nSunday and enjoyed the afternoon\nwith them He leftt home for R'eh\nitond Monday to spend some time\nwith his daughters there.\nCrnxtons Have Guests\nMr. and Mrs. C. W. Hodges, and\nPeggy, spent Sunday a'ternoon in\nRichmond visiting Mr. and Mrs. E\nM Croxton.\nMr. and Mrs. Odham. after a very\nbusy day. motored to Richmond\nThursday night to check on Mrs.\nOdham's father, who was a patient\nin the hospital. They returned to\nRichmond again Saturday and\nbrought him home with them.\nMrs. Robert Jenkins and daugh\nters, Barbara, Nancy and Ann, en\njoyed a beautiful autumn drive Sun\nday and visited Mrs. Jenkins' par\nents, of Cumberland.\nMr. and Mrs. Everett Priddy\nvisited Mr. and Mrs. Woodfin\nHughes Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. C L. Jones, and\nBilly, attended a birthday dinner\nSunday given in honor of Mrs.\n.TnnpR' father'*: AQth hirthriav\nOctogenarian Anticipates\nFor several days Mrs. W B. Gates\nanticipated with pleasure the arrival\nof her two daughters. Virginia and\nBetty, and son. Tommie, for the\nweek end. She took great care to be\nreling fit and fine. Come rain or\nshine Saturday, she joined them for\na shopping tour and lunch in Farm\nville. She then drovewith them to\nCumberland and visited another son\nand his wife, Mr. and Mrs. Jesse\nGates This was not all. Sunday\nmorning she was ready again, and\naccompanied them to church, and\nfrom there, made a call on Mr. and\nMrs. Tom Jenkins. This is the spirit\nthat has kept her young and cheer\nful through her more than 8<i years.\nMr. and Mrs. Edwin Woodward,\nand children, of Richmond, visited\nMiss Mary Bruce and John and J.\nT. Bruce Sunday.\nMrs. Clark Garnett, accompanied\nby her son. Edward, and his family,\nspent a very pleasant, though\ncrowded, day at the Jamestown\nfestival Sunday.\nSisters Gather\nThree sisters of Willie Bradshaw,\nM sdames O. C. Clark. Maud Wall\nand Wilson Suelson. all of Rich\nmond. visited him Saturday in\nSaithside Community Hospital,\nwhe-e in has been a patient for\nEnjoy a \"Magic Carpet \"of Warmth\nin Every Room with the New\nOIL BURNING\n\"EVEN-HEATER\"\nAUTOMATIC THERMOSTATIC FORCED AIR CIRCULATION\nBEAUTIFUL\nCOMPACT\nDEPENDABLE\nECONOMICAL\n\n61,130-BTU OUTPUT\nMODEL NO. SH-62\nW. A. PRICE COMPANY\nAcross from Taylor Mfg, Co. Phone 1033 Formville, Vo,\nover four weeks.\nMr and Mrs. Frank Bruce and\nson. Ronnie, visited Mr. and Mrs.\nAlbert Hillsman Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Jim Wilson, of\nFarmville visa\u2019d and Mrs.\nMercer Gilliam Sunday.\nMrs. Aubrey Glasgow and sons\nspent Sunday afternoon with her\nparents. Her father has been quite\nsick recently.\nGates Kamil\\ Goes to Festival\nMr. and M\u2019\\s. Charlie Gates and\ndaughter. Bettv Jo. attended the\n.tomestown festb'aj and also went\nsightseeing in colonial Williamsburg\nSunday,\nMr. and M-s. Tom Wilson, and\nvoting son. of Richmond, visited Mr.\nand Mrs Drewry Gates Sunday.\nLittle Val finds tho eminfrv far\nmore exciting than the big city. No\nsooner had he landed in ih^ yard\nthan he had chased p^or kittv and\ncaught her by her proud tail.\nPaul Louis had dinner and soent\nthe afternoon with Richard William\nson Sunday. They enjoyed many\nactivities and good times common\nto country boys.\nRemember: \"A little nonsense\nnow and then is relished by the best\nof men.\"\nMeherrin\nRev. and Mrs. R. E. Dunkum.\nMrs. H. L. Queens berry and Mrs.\nL L. Elliott attended the Iola Kidd\nWMU of the Concord association all\nday meeting of nine churches at\nVictoria Baptist church October is.\nHarris Gee. Julian Price. Freddie\nSchmidt and Earnest Herzig visited\nrelatives in Greensboro. N C.. Sun\nday.\nMr. and Mrs. Arthur Price, of tho\nPlymuth community, visited rela\ntives here Sunday.\nTO\nDR REPP^\nthe rescuer\nBe gay with\nthe friendly\n\u201cPepper\nUpper\u201d\nProspect Items\nT he masts, Lanes, Ca rso its~\u00a3ve rye n es\nOff to Williamsburg and Jainesiawn\nThe two hi ivy frosts that came\ni during the week end deepened the\nred. gold and purple hue of the\nj autumn leaves and made the wood\nland a thing of breath-taking beauty\nin the panorama of color, compa\nrable to the famous Skyline drive.\nThere have been several cases of\nflu in this community, but no one\nis really ill with it. not the Asian\nj type.\nC. W. Glenn, of Farmville, spent\n.Sunday evening in the home of his\nmother.\nMrs. A V. Brisentine. Donna Lou\nDoss and Nancy Brisentine spent the\nweek end in New Jersey with Mr.\nand Mrs. Jim McGall.\n:t Go to Jamestown\nMrs. J E. Glenn, Mrs. W. E. Car\nson and Sandra Long spent Sunday\nin Jamestown.\nMr. and Mrs. C. E. Farrar, and\nsons, of Henderson, N. C. were\nguests of their parents Saturday and\nSunday. They, with Mr and Mrs.\n0. P Farrar, spent Saturday in\nRichmond.\nMr. and Mrs. J. F Glenn, Rich\nard. Tony and Steve Glenn went to\nthe Jamestown festival Sunday.\nMrs R B Wilson, of Green Bay,\nspent Friday night with her mother,\nMrs. Wilson. Mrs. Glenn and Stuart\nGlenn were dinner guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. E W Carson in Appo\nmattox.\nMiss Mary Doyne, of Farmville.\nwas a week end guest in the home\nof Mr. and Mrs. Nelson Hix\nMrs. C P Doss and Mrs. Otway\nSmith were in Lynchburg Monday,\nMiss Lane Visits\nMiss Patsy Lane .spent Thursday\nnight with friend in Farmville\nExpected guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nC. A. Garde:, fiut week\nand Mrs. -F C\u201e Shields.\nNeck. .;N. Juttl Mr\nBobby ShieT:.,>s afd two\nNorfolk.\nend are Mr.\nof Scotland\nand Mrs\nchildren, of\nRt-v and Mis Philip Thomas.\nMrs. John Lane. M: Pats Line\nand M:: Ilnb\u2019- L Wednes\nday in Jamestown nd W U.nir\nburs.\nM s. Peter F IN II M t\u201d:a les\nFox. Carolyn S .e Ra n and VYr\nnon Lou Barton, of Roanoke, visited\nMrs. H. J Meredith and M New\nton Brisentirr\u2019 Sunday\nA Squirrel Saves\nfor the Future\u2014\nWHY DON\u2019T\nYOU?\nOpe$ an Account with us now and\nadd something to it each payday.\nr\nPLANTERS\n\\ciih Cs? Co.\nEstoblis led 1867\nMember Federal Reserve System\nT\nX Member Federal Deposit Insurance Corp\nGRAY'S TRULY a drug store\nAT QUIt Ttexott DRUG STORE\nNATIONALLY Al\\ERTISED HEX ALL-GUARANTEED PRODUCTS\n\nSets Fin Cutis\n\nto Stay\nCAR A\nNOME\nMl&ir ROONEY,\nWACt* SiEZAK in\npiyoecHio\niH's 7* *d\u00bbo Spectaci\nI ^Mali's 7 *diO Spectacular j\nSundafSC t.\u201813th NBC\nLCheck flffu; ptper for t\u00bbmej\nSt-itions\n1\nCoughing\nkeep you\nawake?\nFAST SET\nDelicately fragrant hair\nspray conditions with\nlanolin', leaves hair soft,\nlustrous. M\nBIG 11 OZ. CAN\nThe Name KANTLEEK on Rubb\nIs Like Sterling on Silver\nKANTLEEK\nHOT WATER BOTTLE\nCan't leak because it\u2019s\nmade in one\npiece. Holds\nover 2\nquarts.\nGuaranteed\n5 years.\n3.8?\nS\\\u00bb\nCHERROSOTE\n